gs of London, ca. 1600 -- t16. John Day and the Bookshop That Never Was -- t17. Boundary·Disputes in Early Modern London -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1500 and 1700, London grew from a minor national capital to the largest city in Europe. The defining period of growth was the period from 1550 to 1650, the midpoint of which coincided with the end of Elizabeth I's reign and the height of Shakespeare's theatrical career.In Material London, ca. 1600, Lena Cowen Orlin and a distinguished group of social, intellectual, urban, architectural, and agrarian historians, archaeologists, cultural anthropologists, and literary critics explore the ideas, structures, and practices that distinguished London before the Great Fire, basing their investigations on the material traces in artifacts, playtexts, documents, graphic arts, and archaeological remains.In order to evoke "material London, ca. 1600," each scholar examines a different aspect of one of the great world cities at a critical moment in Western history. Several chapters give broad panoramic and authoritative views: what architectural forms characterized the built city around 1600; how the public theatre established its claim on the city; how London's citizens incorporated the new commercialism of their culture into their moral views. Other essays offer sharply focused studies: how Irish mantles were adopted as elite fashions in the hybrid culture of the court; how the city authorities clashed with the church hierarchy over the building of a small bookshop; how London figured in Ben Jonson's exploration of the role of the poet.Although all the authors situate the material world of early modern London—its objects, products, literatures, built environment, and economic practices—in its broader political and cultural contexts, provocative debates and exchanges remain both within and between the essays as to what constitutes "material London, ca. 1600."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aWorld History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWorld History.1 aArcher, Ian W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlayney, Peter W.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman, Alice T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFumerton, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGurr, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Jean E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Ann Rosalind, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeene, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrlin, Lena Cowen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrlin, Lena Cowen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPaster, Gail Kern, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeck, Linda Levy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSacks, David Harris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchneider, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchofield, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSinfield, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStallybrass, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThirsk, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook p